comments.body:
Another perspective on being case-kept and case-insensitive: though most modern file system are case-sensitive, a lot of high-level API set, e.g. Win32, adopts case-kept and case-insensitive. AFAIK, the default setting on Mac doesn't allow two files whose names differ only by case.

Summary till now:
1. A script package named `<abc>` will contain (by itself) only one script named `<abc>.ps1`, till now;
2. It is possible to publish `<abc>.ps1.ps1` to the repo, but no one has done that yet;
3. A script package can have external dependency, therefore `Save-Script` might give several script files, and this is a current practice;
4. The only cross-platform-compatible way is to use both extensions and shebang line, and being case-insensitive.

Because of point 3, I am against allowing the user to save `Get-UpTime` package by invoking `Save-Script -Name Get-UpTime.ps1`. This could cause confusion because you are not only saving one script file.

Point 4 arises from a broader topic on cross-platform PSGallery.
